  - title: Throw the code away. The specification is the asset; the codebase is a disposable projection you regenerate on demand.
  - title: The plan computes itself. Drydock derives the dependency graph from typed specification files and orders the build вЂ” there is no hand-written task list.
  - title: A second build costs almost nothing. Edit the specification and only the phases whose typed interface or route actually moved are rebuilt.
  - title: Staleness survives a git clone. Rebuild decisions key off a content hash of every input, not a file timestamp, so a fresh checkout still knows exactly what is current.
  - title: The build cannot skip the human. Every phase emits evidence and stops at the Console; nothing proceeds until you sign off вЂ” in phased and agile runs alike.
