## What Drydock is

Drydock builds software from a specification in four steps: **Setup** a specification, **Build** a
plan, **Run** the plan into software, **Iterate** on the specification. The four steps contain seven
operations that map directly to the GitHub Spec Kit command surface. Changes are made to the
specification, never to the code.

```mermaid
flowchart LR
  classDef dir    fill:#0a5c38,stroke:#2cb67d,color:#fff,font-weight:bold
  classDef md     fill:#d4a017,stroke:#a07810,color:#111,font-weight:bold
  classDef script fill:#1e40af,stroke:#3b5fc0,color:#fff
  classDef output fill:#6d28d9,stroke:#8b5cf6,color:#fff,font-weight:bold
  SET[setup]:::script --> SPEC(["Specification/"]):::dir
  SPEC --> BP[build_plan]:::script
  BP --> PLAN{{"BUILD_PLAN.md"}}:::md
  PLAN --> RUN[run]:::script
  RUN --> OUT(["Working Software"]):::output
  OUT --> IT[iterate]:::script
  IT -.-> SPEC
```

## Step 1 вЂ” Setup

Produce a specification directory. Setup does not create the code target вЂ” Run does.

### 1.1 Scaffold

`drydock new <Project>` drops a starter specification from templates; you prune it вЂ” rename the
Example files, delete what does not apply. Two files are always required: `METADATA.md` (project
identity вЂ” name, display name, short description, status, stack) and `INTENT.md` (governing
intent). Everything else is conditional on the project type.

> Parallels Spec Kit `/constitution` вЂ” establishes the project's governing intent and selects the
> opinionated stack files that govern development guidelines for every build session.

### 1.2 The Intent.md File

```markdown
# INTENT: <Project>

| Field        | Value                                        |
|--------------|----------------------------------------------|
| Project Name | Human-readable display name                  |
| Description  | One sentence вЂ” reused as METADATA.short_description. |
| Stack        | python.md, flask.md, sqlite.md, bootstrap5.md |
| Version      | YYYYMMDD V1                                  |

## Intent

The single question this project answers вЂ” what you are building and why it must
exist. A short paragraph, not a feature list. Everything downstream is judged
against this.

## Goals

- One measurable goal per line.

## Constraints

- One hard limit per line.

## Success Criteria

- One testable outcome per line.
```

Stack files are opinionated and prescriptive: each defines naming conventions, structural patterns,
and testing requirements for one technology, and is injected verbatim into every AI agent session
that handles that technology. Declaring `python.md, flask.md, sqlite.md` in `INTENT.md` is the
complete act of configuration вЂ” every phase prompt that touches those layers receives the rules
automatically. Stack files are the governing development guidelines for the project.

```
stack/
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ language/
в”‚   в””в”Ђв”Ђ python.md
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ web/
в”‚   в”њв”Ђв”Ђ flask.md
в”‚   в”њв”Ђв”Ђ fastapi.md
в”‚   в””в”Ђв”Ђ django.md
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ frontend/
в”‚   в”њв”Ђв”Ђ bootstrap5.md
в”‚   в””в”Ђв”Ђ ui-flask.bootstrap-client.md
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ persistence/
в”‚   в”њв”Ђв”Ђ sqlite.md
в”‚   в”њв”Ђв”Ђ postgres.md
в”‚   в””в”Ђв”Ђ persistence.md
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ cloud-aws/
в”‚   в”њв”Ђв”Ђ aws-lambda.md
в”‚   в”њв”Ђв”Ђ aws-api-gateway.md
в”‚   в”њв”Ђв”Ђ aws-dynamodb.md
в”‚   в”њв”Ђв”Ђ aws-s3.md
в”‚   в”њв”Ђв”Ђ aws-sqs.md
в”‚   в””в”Ђв”Ђ alexa-skills-kit.md
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ infra-ci/
в”‚   в”њв”Ђв”Ђ terraform.md
в”‚   в””в”Ђв”Ђ github-actions.md
в””в”Ђв”Ђ shared/
    в”њв”Ђв”Ђ common.md
    в””в”Ђв”Ђ marina-library.md
```

### 1.3 Create Specification Files

The scaffold contains example files (`SCREEN-Example.md`, `FEATURE-Example.md`). Rename them for
your project and delete files that do not apply вЂ” `DATABASE.md` if there is no persistence,
`SCREEN-*.md` if there is no UI. The minimum required set is `METADATA.md`, `INTENT.md`,
`ARCHITECTURE.md`, and at least one `FEATURE-*.md`.

> Parallels Spec Kit `/specify` вЂ” authoring the typed specification files the build engine reads.
> Where Spec Kit writes a single `spec.md`, Drydock decomposes into typed files owned by the
> dependency graph.

**Validate before building:**

```
bash bin/validate.sh <ProjectName>
```

| | |
|---|---|
| **What it checks** | Required files present; METADATA fields populated; naming conventions; no example files remaining; `## Open Questions` section in every applicable file; stack files declared in `Stack` field exist in the library |
| **Exit** | `0` = ready to build В· `1` = errors listed |

#### 1.3.1 Decompose вЂ” reverse-engineer existing code

Use this when the project already exists as running code and you want Drydock to own it going
forward.

```
bash bin/decompose.sh <ProjectPath> > decompose-prompt.md
bash bin/decompose.sh <ProjectPath> --spec-name <Name> > decompose-prompt.md
```

| | |
|---|---|
| **`<ProjectPath>`** | Absolute path to the project directory, or a project name under `../` |
| **`--spec-name`** | Override the output specification directory name (default: directory basename) |
| **Output** | Writes to stdout вЂ” pipe to a file, then feed to an AI agent |
| **What it does** | Reads the source code, detects the stack, and generates a prompt. The AI agent writes the conformed specification files; paste them into `Specifications/<Name>/` |

```
# Example
bash bin/decompose.sh ../GAME > decompose-prompt.md
# Feed decompose-prompt.md to an AI agent в†’ paste output into Specifications/GAME/
```

> Parallels Spec Kit `/analyze` вЂ” analyzing an existing codebase to produce a specification.

#### 1.3.2 Analyze вЂ” conform an imported specification

Use this when you already have specification documents written outside of Drydock вЂ” notes, a
design doc, a Spec Kit export. `analyze` converts them into typed Drydock specification files so
the build engine can read them.

```
bash bin/setup.sh <ProjectName> --analyze
```

| | |
|---|---|
| **`<ProjectName>`** | Name of the directory under `specification_directory` |
| **What it does** | Renames existing `.md` files to `.imported`, then calls an AI agent to write conformed replacements in the Drydock typed format (`FEATURE-*.md`, `SCREEN-*.md`, etc.) |
| **Auto-triggered** | If the directory contains `.md` files but no `METADATA.md`, `setup.sh` switches to analyze mode automatically |

> Parallels Spec Kit `/analyze` вЂ” converting external specification artifacts into the Drydock
> typed format. `/analyze` in Spec Kit surfaces gaps; `--analyze` here converts the input.

#### 1.3.3 Clarify вЂ” resolve open questions

Before building, every specification file must have its `## Open Questions` section resolved.
`spec_iterate.sh` runs an AI gap analysis that surfaces ambiguities and scores the specification
across seven dimensions.

```
bash bin/spec_iterate.sh <ProjectName>
```

| | |
|---|---|
| **`<ProjectName>`** | Name of the specification directory |
| **What it does** | AI gap analysis; updates `REFERENCE_GAPS.md` (unresolved questions), `SPEC_SCORECARD.md` (7-dimension quality score), `SPEC_ITERATION.md` (improvement suggestions) |
| **When to run** | After adding or changing specification files; always before `build_plan` |

Resolve each `## Open Questions` entry вЂ” manually or with the AI's suggestions вЂ” then re-run
until the scorecard is clean.

> Parallels Spec Kit `/clarify` вЂ” surfacing and resolving ambiguities before building. Where Spec
> Kit clarifies interactively, Drydock scores the full specification across seven dimensions and
> tracks every unresolved question.

